            <!-- last section article content -->
            <section>
                
                <div class="">
                    <img src="/media/news/landing_pics/sub_pic/Prince.jpg" alt="Papa J and Prince — the men roped into Phala Phala burglary ‘mastermind’s’ escape to Namibia" title="Papa J and Prince — the men roped into Phala Phala burglary ‘mastermind’s’ escape to Namibia"/>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-xs">
                        Prince Mazibuku</p>
                </div>
                
                <article>
                    
                    <p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">The alleged details of the Phala Phala burglary were first exposed in an affidavit by former spy boss Arthur Fraser, in which he accused Ramaphosa and the head of the VIP protection unit, Wally Rhoode, of criminality in concealing the theft and in the detention and interrogation of some of the suspects.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Ramaphosa has largely kept mum on the allegations, except to acknowledge that the burglary did take place, and to state that the money that was stolen was not from the proceeds of crime and was far less than what Fraser claimed.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Fraser did not put a fixed figure to the stolen cash, saying the information he received from a member of Rhoode&rsquo;s team was &ldquo;speculated to be in the region of approximately about $4-million to $8-million&rdquo;.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">In the audio recording, David is heard claiming that the figure was much lower because they only stole a portion of the cash hidden in the sofa at the farm.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">He tells his interrogators that a cleaner working at Ramaphosa&rsquo;s directed him to the money that was stored in the leather sofa and brought him samples of the cash to prove that it was authentic.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">He describes the operation as &ldquo;easy&rdquo; and says it required no violence.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">He tells the unidentified men that the robbers only took about $800,000 (about R13-million) packaged in eight wrapped parcels containing $100,000 each.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">&ldquo;That lady [the cleaner] said don&rsquo;t take everything because you are dealing with the president, they are going to fuck you up and they are going to fuck me up,&rdquo; he explains.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">He also gives details about how he crossed into Namibia, saying he left because he sensed that &ldquo;this thing is too hot&rdquo;. David claims he was arrested because someone who did not get paid from the stolen cash snitched on him.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">From the description in the recording, it appears that police raided a Milnerton property where David and other suspects were staying in 2020 after the robbery.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">David describes the raid, saying police beat the suspects and even took out the &ldquo;whole ceiling of the house&rdquo; looking for the money, but the suspects told the police that it had been spent. He claims that they were dumped &ldquo;in the bush&rdquo; after the raid.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Interestingly, the recording includes the claim that David&rsquo;s father worked for the state and was somehow connected to the Namibian vice-president.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">The content of the recording suggests the fallout from Fraser&rsquo;s disclosure could potentially be embarrassing for the Namibian political leadership, not just for Ramaphosa.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Recall that David was collected from the border by Ngalangi, the Fishcor executive.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Notably, CID chief Becker, who compiled the report on David, was one of the key investigators of the so-called Fishrot scandal, which saw millions of Namibian dollars in fishing quota fees collected by Fishcor diverted to executives, but with a significant cut going to the ruling party, Swapo.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">It is also notable that Becker was unexpectedly moved across from the CID to the police&rsquo;s forensics division in mid-July 2020, a month after David&rsquo;s arrest &mdash; a move that has raised eyebrows&nbsp;since he had been in charge of the CID for less than a year.</span></span></p>

<h4><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:#4f81bd"><strong><em><span style="color:black">&lsquo;No man&rsquo;s land&rsquo;</span></em></strong></span></span></h4>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Since news of Fraser&rsquo;s complaint broke, South African officials, contrary to claims made by Namibian police, have denied receiving a request from the Namibians for mutual legal assistance in investigating David.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">The Namibian Police Force&rsquo;s (Nampol) Inspector-General, Sebastian Ndeitunga released a statement saying their officers met with their South African counterparts in &ldquo;no man&rsquo;s land&rdquo; in the Noordoewer-Karas border region on 19 June 2020, shortly after Imanuwela&rsquo;s arrest.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">The meeting is corroborated in the Namibian police report, though the identity of the South African official that engaged Namibian authorities to set up the meeting in &ldquo;no man&rsquo;s land&rdquo; is blacked out of the police report.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Ndeitunga said the officials shared &ldquo;operational information pertaining to Mr David Imanuwela and other Namibian nationals&rdquo; suspected of involvement in the break-in at Ramaphosa&rsquo;s farm.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">After identifying &ldquo;individuals, bank accounts, and various properties including lodges, houses and vehicles suspected to have been purchased with the proceeds of crime&rdquo;, and having obtained a preservation order, Namibian authorities turned to South Africa&rsquo;s ministry of justice to &ldquo;to confirm whether or not a crime was registered in South Africa&rdquo;.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">However, according to Ndeitunga&rsquo;s statement, &ldquo;</span>no response was received from South African authorities, resulting in the cancellation of the preservation order and release of assets&rdquo;.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">In his affidavit, Fraser claimed that after the robbery Ramaphosa asked for assistance from Namibia&rsquo;s president Hage Geingob in apprehending David. &ldquo;This resulted in Major General Rhoode travelling to Namibia where the suspect was interviewed and stolen monies seized from him. Major General Rhoode had travelled to Namibia utilising official government resources and had not been legally processed through border control.&rdquo;&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">A commissioner of the Namibian police&rsquo;s Special&nbsp;</span>Branch who attended the no man&rsquo;s land meeting, and whose name is also redacted, confirmed that David &ldquo;was the mastermind behind the burglary and supplied some names and photographs of his accomplices&rdquo;, according to the police report.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">The report added: &ldquo;Due to the sensitivity of the matter and the envisaged fallout it will create in South Africa they requested that the matter is handled with discretion.&rdquo;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">It also noted that the two presidents were &ldquo;allegedly&rdquo; engaged in ongoing discussions.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Geingob has strongly denied allegations that he assisted Ramaphosa in covering up the theft.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">Justice Minister Ronald Lamola&rsquo;s spokesperson, Chrispin Phiri said there was a specific process that countries had to follow when applying for mutual legal assistance which involved liaising through the country&rsquo;s respective embassy or high commission.&nbsp;</span></span></p>

<p><span style="background-color:white"><span style="color:black">&ldquo;We can confirm that, to date, all requests for mutual legal assistance have followed these processes without any complications between the two states Namibia and South Africa. We can categorically state that, to date, there is no official record of this specific request,&rdquo; Phiri said in a statement.&nbsp;</span><strong>DM</strong></span></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
                    
                </article>
            </section>
